Even within the cutthroat beauty business, there is no subcategory more fie=
rcely
contested than women=E2=80=99s fragrance. Chanel, Dior, YSL Beauty, and a f=
ew others have historically dominated, cycling in and out of the top spots =
and spending lavishly to establish and defend their positions. Which is why=
 I was shocked to learn that the past year=E2=80=99s bestselling women=E2=
=80=99s fragrance franchise is not from one of the Big Three, but=E2=80=A6 =
Carolina Herrera=E2=80=99s Good Girl, the citrusy-sweet perfume that comes =
bottled in a mini stiletto heel.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Incredibly, according to Circana consumer data, Good Girl isn=E2=80=99t jus=
t the top perfume brand in the U.S.; it was also the bestselling women=E2=
=80=99s fragrance in the world last year, supplanting Chanel=E2=80=99s Chan=
ce. (Valentino Donna, Dior=E2=80=99s Miss Dior, and Chanel=E2=80=99s Coco M=
ademoiselle round out the rest of the top five.) Yes, yes, these rankings a=
re estimates, compiled from a number of data points, so take them with a gr=
ain of salt. But the dethroning of Chanel,
long the category leader, is a huge deal.

=C2=A0

Carolina Herrera=E2=80=99s momentum may not be surprising to analysts who=
=E2=80=99ve spent time on TikTok, which has helped propel the brand. But th=
e real credit goes to Puig, the Spanish beauty and fashion conglomerate tha=
t acquired Carolina Herrera in 1995, transforming a company best known for =
its gala wear into one of the world=E2=80=99s biggest sellers of designer f=
ragrances. More
recently, Puig has been at the forefront of some of beauty=E2=80=99s bigges=
t M&A deals, acquiring a majority stake in Charlotte Tilbury in 2020 and By=
redo in 2022. Puig went public last May in the largest European offering of=
 2024.=C2=A0

=C2=A0

Long before the I.P.O., however, Puig began laying the groundwork for the u=
pmarket consumer strategy that=E2=80=99s now paying dividends. The company =
spent the past two decades
reinventing itself from a regional mass market player to compete with LVMH,=
 L=E2=80=99Or=C3=A9al, and Coty. In 2022, Puig reached 10 percent worldwide=
 market share of =E2=80=9Cselective fragrances,=E2=80=9D a subcategory that=
 includes designer perfumes, more than tripling its market share since 2004=
=2E=C2=A0

=C2=A0

At its earnings call tomorrow, Puig is expected to announce that it has sur=
passed 11 percent market share. =E2=80=9CA lot of Puig=E2=80=99s [previous]=
 business was
in mass market, and mostly in Spain, and they stopped all of this=E2=80=93=
=E2=80=93which was profitable=E2=80=93=E2=80=93and decided to focus on frag=
rance and fashion and nothing else until they commanded 10 percent of marke=
t share in fragrance,=E2=80=9D said a person with knowledge of their trajec=
tory.

Social
Media & Sex Appeal
------------------

Puig has pursued a disruptive marketing strategy, too. In 2008, the company=
 went
rogue in the best way, launching Paco Rabanne=E2=80=99s 1 Million cologne w=
ith a fairly radical brand play. Instead of selling romance or sensuality, =
like everyone else, the scent told a story about wealth and power=E2=80=93=
=E2=80=93a provocative idea in fragrance marketing at the time. Now, Rabann=
e drives more than $1 billion in sales.

=C2=A0

Good Girl followed a similar trajectory. The original eau de
parfum, which smells of jasmine and tonka beans, launched in 2016 with the =
slightly cringey, ultimately catchy tagline =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s so good t=
o be bad=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94which sort of runs counter to what Carolina Herre=
ra, the brand and the person, are known for: beautiful dresses and gowns fo=
r rich ladies who lunch and attend galas. =E2=80=9CGood Girl runs so far fr=
om Carolina=E2=80=99s DNA=E2=80=93=E2=80=93which is genius,=E2=80=9D an ins=
ider said.

=C2=A0

At the
time Good Girl launched, Carolina Herrera de Baez told me the concept was i=
nspired by her mother=E2=80=99s conviction that mystery is one of the most =
important qualities a woman can have. The scent and packaging=E2=80=94an ic=
onic navy high heel=E2=80=94embodies the notion of Herrera=E2=80=99s ideali=
zed customer as both elegant and a little bit naughty. (Model Karlie Kloss =
has been the face of the fragrance since its inception.)

=C2=A0

Marketing spin aside, it was clear early on that Good Girl was destined to =
be huge. Just seven months after its debut, I reported that the fragrance w=
as on track to double its initial sales projections in its first year and h=
it around $100 million in revenue. Puig has manufactured Carolina Herrera=
=E2=80=99s fragrances for 37 years, but it=E2=80=99s only in the past decad=
e that the group has explicitly focused on building the brand=E2=80=99s fra=
grance franchises. In
2015, Carolina Herrera=E2=80=99s perfumes were a solid rough $300 million b=
usiness, still nothing to sneeze at, with the majority of sales coming from=
 outside the U.S. Since then, revenues have multiplied (they=E2=80=99re sti=
ll $1 billion) and globalized. (Puig and Carolina Herrera declined to comme=
nt on sales figures or specific brand rankings.)

=C2=A0

Meanwhile, Puig continues to differentiate itself by ignoring its
competitors. L=E2=80=99Or=C3=A9al and Coty, for example, hold the majority =
of designer fragrance licensees, which means they=E2=80=99re at the mercy o=
f the brands who hire them to create, manufacture, and distribute their pro=
ducts. If a brand isn=E2=80=99t happy with their licensor, they can just ta=
ke their business elsewhere. (Gucci, which has been pretty vocal about its =
disappointment with Coty, will likely take its beauty line in-house after t=
heir deal ends.) As a result, the L=E2=80=99Or=C3=A9al-Coty rivalry is amon=
g the fiercest in
the industry. Puig has sidestepped that designer licensing arms race: Ninet=
y-five percent of its business comes from its wholly owned brands.

=C2=A0

Beyond the strong brand story or clever packaging, however, the success of =
Good Girl contains a lesson about social media, too. Good Girl is a fixture=
 on TikTok and one of few designer fragrances that get a lot of airtime acr=
oss PerfumeTok, where perfume collectors show off their
stashes. Good Girl was recently featured in a video called =E2=80=9CPerfume=
s that make men go crazy=E2=80=9D that racked up 1.3 million views. Another=
, which had 3.3 million views, features Good Girl as a top =E2=80=9Csexy=E2=
=80=9D fragrance. =E2=80=9CThis is the reference point for today=E2=80=99s =
generation,=E2=80=9D said an executive with knowledge of Puig=E2=80=99s bus=
iness. Or maybe, in a visual medium like TikTok, there=E2=80=99s still noth=
ing sexier than a stiletto-shaped bottle.

