<table width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" role=
=3D"presentation" style=3D"mso-table-lspace:0pt;mso-table-rspace:0pt;word-b=
reak:break-word;"><tbody><tr><td style=3D"padding-bottom:32px;"><div style=
=3D"color:#000000;direction:ltr;font-family:&#39;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;=
;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0px;line-height:150%;text-al=
ign:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0p=
x;">Puig has pursued a disruptive marketing strategy, too. In 2008, the com=
pany went
rogue in the best way<em>,</em> launching Paco Rabanne=E2=80=99s 1 Million =
cologne with a fairly radical brand play. Instead of selling romance or sen=
suality, like everyone else, the scent told a story about wealth and power=
=E2=80=93=E2=80=93a provocative idea in fragrance marketing at the time. No=
w, Rabanne drives more than $1 billion in sales.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;ma=
rgin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Good G=
irl followed a similar trajectory. The original <em>eau de
parfum</em>, which smells of jasmine and tonka beans, launched in 2016 with=
 the slightly cringey, ultimately catchy tagline =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s so g=
ood to be bad=E2=80=9D=E2=80=94which sort of runs counter to what Carolina =
Herrera, the brand <em>and</em> the person, are known for: beautiful dresse=
s and gowns for rich ladies who lunch and attend galas. =E2=80=9CGood Girl =
runs so far from Carolina=E2=80=99s DNA=E2=80=93=E2=80=93which is genius,=
=E2=80=9D an insider said.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=
=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">At the
time Good Girl launched, <strong>Carolina Herrera de Baez</strong> told me =
the concept was inspired by her mother=E2=80=99s conviction that <em>myster=
y</em> is one of the most important qualities a woman can have. The scent a=
nd packaging=E2=80=94an iconic navy high heel=E2=80=94embodies the notion o=
f Herrera=E2=80=99s idealized customer as both elegant and a little bit nau=
ghty. (Model <strong>Karlie Kloss</strong> has been the face of the fragran=
ce since its inception.)</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0=
</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Marketing spin aside, it was c=
lear early on that Good Girl was destined to be huge. Just seven months aft=
er its debut, I reported that the fragrance was on track to <em>double</em>=
 its initial sales projections in its first year and hit around $100 millio=
n in revenue. Puig has manufactured Carolina Herrera=E2=80=99s fragrances f=
or <em>37 years</em>, but it=E2=80=99s only in the past decade that the gro=
up has explicitly focused on building the brand=E2=80=99s fragrance franchi=
ses. In
2015, Carolina Herrera=E2=80=99s perfumes were a solid rough $300 million b=
usiness, still nothing to sneeze at, with the majority of sales coming from=
 <em>outside</em> the U.S. Since then, revenues have multiplied (they=E2=80=
=99re still $1 billion) and globalized. (Puig and Carolina Herrera declined=
 to comment on sales figures or specific brand rankings.)</p><p style=3D"ma=
rgin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px=
;">Meanwhile, Puig continues to differentiate itself by ignoring its
competitors. L=E2=80=99Or=C3=A9al and Coty, for example, hold the majority =
of designer fragrance licensees, which means they=E2=80=99re at the mercy o=
f the brands who hire them to create, manufacture, and distribute their pro=
ducts. If a brand isn=E2=80=99t happy with their licensor, they can just ta=
ke their business elsewhere. (Gucci, which has been pretty vocal about its =
disappointment with Coty, will likely take its beauty line in-house after t=
heir deal ends.) As a result, the L=E2=80=99Or=C3=A9al-Coty rivalry is amon=
g the fiercest in
the industry. Puig has sidestepped that designer licensing arms race: Ninet=
y-five percent of its business comes from its wholly owned brands.</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Beyond=
 the strong brand story or clever packaging, however, the success of Good G=
irl contains a lesson about social media, too. Good Girl is a fixture on Ti=
kTok and one of few designer fragrances that get a lot of airtime across Pe=
rfumeTok, where perfume collectors show off their
stashes. Good Girl was recently featured in a video called =E2=80=9CPerfume=
s that make men go crazy=E2=80=9D that racked up 1.3 million views. Another=
, which had 3.3 million views, features Good Girl as a top =E2=80=9Csexy=E2=
=80=9D fragrance. =E2=80=9CThis is the reference point for today=E2=80=99s =
generation,=E2=80=9D said an executive with knowledge of Puig=E2=80=99s bus=
iness. Or maybe, in a visual medium like TikTok, there=E2=80=99s still noth=
ing sexier than a stiletto-shaped bottle.</p></div>
